Inca Emperor whose birthplace is still the subject of speculation and has not been categorically identified, although there are three cities that dispute this honor: Quito, capital of Ecuador, Cusco and Caranqui. The interest that he has generated in the story lies in the fact that at the time the Spanish settlers arrived, he was in command of the Inca Empire. His figure is related to a civil war that had his brother Huáscar as its counterpart. For 10 points, name the Inca who was the last regent of this civilization that was born in Lake Titicaca.

Typical ceremony of the Andean (mountain range running along the western side of South America) peoples. Although this tradition is celebrated in many South American countries, it has as a common note its Inca origin. Upon the arrival of the Spanish colonizers, this festivity was revoked as it was considered pagan and contrary to the Catholic faith. It was replaced with Corpus Christi. To this day, it has been celebrated again as a way of honoring the indigenous past of the original peoples. Its celebration coincides with the summer solstice. This celebration is a tribute to Taita Inti or Sun God, for allowing the fertility of Pachamama or Mother Earth, for which a pambamesa is made to share food, in this context corn has a starring role. For 10 points, name the ceremony that is commemorated in the Andean world and that in Spanish means Fiesta del Sol.
